lyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/status/1","description":"The issue is open and ready for the assignee to start work on it.","iconUrl":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/images/icons/statuses/open.png","name":"Open","id":"1","statusCategory":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/statuscategory/2","id":2,"key":"new","colorName":"blue-gray","name":"To Do"}},"components":[],"timeoriginalestimate":null,"description":"The section on updating service image, http://docs.hpcloud.com/eucalyptus/4.2.1/#install-guide/upgrade_from_oldv.html,  is outdated and incomplete.\r\n\r\nThe outdated part is that imaging worker is managed via cloudformation. So, steps 2 and 3 would be:\r\n2. Delete curent stack {{esi-manage-stack -a delete imaging}}\r\n3. Wait until stack has been deleted {{esi-manage-stack -a check imaging}}\r\n4. Create a new stack that will have the new service image in the configuration {{esi-manage-stack -a create imaging}}\r\n\r\nThere is no mention of how to update running ELBs. {{esi-install-image --install-default}} will set the cloud property for the semi to use as ELB service instances but running ELBs are not updated. I think we call this fact out but we should document ways to actually update the image that running ELBs use and there are actually a couple ways to achieve this.\r\n\r\n# Delete the load balancer and recreate it. The result of this is new security group and other changes from the original running ELB but the ELB service instance will be running the latest emi.\r\n# -manually create a new launch config that uses the new service image emi. Update the existing ELB's autoscaling group to use the new launch config. Terminate existing instances of ELB service image. AutoScaling will launch a new instance to replace it and it will be of the new emi.-  this probably does not work and needs to be verified by QA\r\n\r\n\r\n  ","customfield_13000":null,"customfield_13200":null,"customfield_11300":null,"customfield_11500":null,"timetracking":{}